and it also goes here.

00:01:09.150 --> 00:01:12.230
If you look at all the points
that are specified by all of

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:15.750
the scaled up or scaled down or
negative scaled versions of

00:01:15.750 --> 00:01:17.880
this vector, you're going to
get all the points on this

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:20.640
line if you draw those vectors
in standard position.

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:23.540
So this is my line
right there.

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:27.050
Now, I want to construct a
linear transformation that

00:01:27.050 --> 00:01:29.730
reflects around this line.

00:01:29.730 --> 00:01:33.660
For example, if I have
this vector-- let me

00:01:33.660 --> 00:01:34.570
draw it like this.

00:01:34.570 --> 00:01:37.480
Let's say I have that vector
that specifies that point

00:01:37.480 --> 00:01:38.710
right there.

00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:40.490
Let me call that vector x.

00:01:40.490 --> 00:01:44.770
I want the transformation of
x to be essentially the

00:01:44.770 --> 00:01:46.540
reflection of x around
this line.

00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:50.410
So if I go in this direction
right here, I want this to be

00:01:50.410 --> 00:01:52.520
the transformation.

00:01:52.520 --> 00:01:55.885
I want that to be the
transformation of x, so it

00:01:55.885 --> 00:01:57.300
should look just like that.

00:01:57.300 --> 00:01:58.840
I'll do another example.

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:00.935
Let's say I have this vector.

00:02:03.570 --> 00:02:05.250
Let me give you a particular
vector.

00:02:05.250 --> 00:02:08.229
Let's say I have a vector that's
orthogonal to my line.

00:02:08.229 --> 00:02:11.039
So let's say I have the vector,
I'll call it v1.

00:02:11.039 --> 00:02:13.150
And let's see, something that's
orthogonal to it, I can

00:02:13.150 --> 00:02:15.750
switch these two guys and make
one of them negative.

00:02:15.750 --> 00:02:22.040
So if I go to the vector 2,
minus 1, so if I have this

00:02:22.040 --> 00:02:26.850
vector right here, visually
it looks orthogonal.

00:02:26.850 --> 00:02:30.380
So if I have v2-- let
me call it v1.

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:36.780
v1 is equal to 2 minus 1.

00:02:36.780 --> 00:02:39.700
Visually, it looks orthogonal,
but then even if you actually

00:02:39.700 --> 00:02:43.670
take the dot product 2 times 1
plus minus 1 times 2, that's

00:02:43.670 --> 00:02:44.270
going to be equal to 0.

00:02:44.270 --> 00:02:47.450
So this is definitely orthogonal
to my spanning

00:02:47.450 --> 00:02:49.290
vector, so it's definitely
orthogonal to every

00:02:49.290 --> 00:02:50.560
point on that line.

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:52.820
But if I apply the
transformation to this guy

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:55.130
right here, I'm just going
to flip it over the line.

00:02:55.130 --> 00:02:57.240
So let me draw it like this.

00:02:57.240 --> 00:03:00.160
So it's going to be equal to--
it's just going to look like--

00:03:00.160 --> 00:03:02.300
let me do it in a green color.

00:03:02.300 --> 00:03:05.360
So the transformation of this
guy, I'm just flipping him

00:03:05.360 --> 00:03:06.030
over this line.

00:03:06.030 --> 00:03:08.060
I'm finding the reflection
across line L.

00:03:08.060 --> 00:03:13.360
So this is going to be the
transformation of v1, and it

00:03:13.360 --> 00:03:18.430
would be-- we don't know what
the actual transformation

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:20.340
matrix is and that's actually
going to be the subject of

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:23.000
this video, but if you just
look at the transformation

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.570
just for v1, it's going to be
the negative of that, so it's

00:03:25.570 --> 00:03:30.770
going to be minus 2, 1.

00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:33.550
So I know I want to define
this transformation.

00:03:33.550 --> 00:03:39.240
I know I want to define this
transformation from R2 to R2.

00:03:39.240 --> 00:03:41.240
That is a reflection.

00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:53.070
So the transformation of some
vector x is the reflection of

00:03:53.070 --> 00:03:58.770
x around or across, or however
you want to describe it,

00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:02.660
around line L, around L.

00:04:02.660 --> 00:04:05.470
Now, in the past, if we wanted
to find the transformation

00:04:05.470 --> 00:04:07.033
matrix-- we know this is a
linear transformation.

00:04:07.033 --> 00:04:11.430
I don't have to go through all
of the exercise of this is a

00:04:11.430 --> 00:04:12.580
linear transformation.

00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:15.380
But in the past, if we wanted
to find the transformation

00:04:15.380 --> 00:04:17.370
matrix for a linear
transformation, let's say we

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:22.130
say T of x is equal to some
2-by-2 matrix, because it's a

00:04:22.130 --> 00:04:25.590
mapping from R2 to R2 times x.

00:04:25.590 --> 00:04:30.110
Before in the past to find A, we
would say A is equal to the

00:04:30.110 --> 00:04:36.180
transformation applied to our
first standard basis vector,

00:04:36.180 --> 00:04:40.040
so the transformation
